ce:section.ce:para:
The MLR curves of four electrolytes during tests under low pressures are shown in Fig. 2
                        . After ignition, the MLR rises rapidly and enters the stage of stable combustion without an obvious peak value. The fluctuation of MLR in this stage is smaller than that in carbonate mixed solvent (see Fig. 3
                        ). After a period of stable combustion, the MLR decreases rapidly. According to the analysis in section 3.1, the combustion in the stable combustion stage of electrolyte is mainly maintained by the low-boiling point carbonate. Comparing the stable stage in Fig. 2 and stage 1 in Fig. 3, the MLR in the stable stage is more stable and the difference between the three flame retardant additives is smaller. It can be seen that the effect of the flame retardant additive is weakened in the presence of LiPF6. Among the three flame retardant additives, HPCTP shows better flame retardant performance, with an average MLR reduction of 6.3%, and a maximum MLR reduction of 8.9% compared with the electrolytes without additives, respectively at 60 kPa.
